				\begin{document}$$uk(R + a) = ei(k.R)uk\left( R \right)$$\end{document}In the above three equations, u(R) is the displacement vector; C(R) and ρ(R) are the elastic constant and mass density of the materials, respectively; k is the wave vector in the first Brillouin zone; uk (R) is the displacement vector in the one-unit cell; and a is the base vector in the direct lattice vector. The frequency band structure and values of Eigen frequency as a function of wave vector can be obtained by solving Eq. 1–3. The calculations were conducted by using commercial software (Comsol Multiphysics 6.0). For the present calculations, three constants, namely, mass density ρ, Young’s modulus E, and Poisson’s ratio ν, are needed, and the parameter values adopted for crystalline silicon were ρ = 2330 kg/m3, E = 169 GPa, and ν = 0.28 for c-Si31–33.
